  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison discusses photographs of the Villard children, which were sent by Fanny Garrison Villard. William L. Garrison warns against inclining Harold Villard&apos;s mind toward militarism. He thinks Oswald Villard is a &quot;noble looking baby.&quot; Helen Villard &quot;has a place in the very core&quot; of William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s heart, and he takes a deep interest in her development. Fanny G. Villard&apos;s description of Heidelberg makes William L. Garrison want to go there again. William L. Garrison cautions Fanny G. Villard against becoming fatigued by too many visitors.</subfield>
